Even if you could get the alt-names to work, It still won't work with &quot;climb XXX&quot; because &quot;climb&quot; is already a verb. So if you type &quot;climb up stairs&quot;, it will say something about not being able to find &quot;up stairs&quot;. You're also mixing verbs in with your alt names, which doesn't make sense conceptually. Verbs are things you do; names and alt names are what you do things to. It might work in some cases, but it smells like a hack. <!-- s:) --><img src="{SMILIES_PATH}/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><!-- s:) -->

What I would do is create a command to cover the cases you want, and then put it in the room where the exit is. That way, it will only happen in the that room, and you can make the text what you want. (It's similar to your &quot;add a verb&quot; approach&quot;, but allows you to specify exactly what you want.) Here is a sample:

[code:hfzhk7pd]    &lt;command name=&quot;climbstairs&quot;&gt;
      &lt;pattern&gt;climb stairs; climb up stairs; ascend stairs&lt;/pattern&gt;
      &lt;script&gt;
        params = NewDictionary()
        dictionary add (params, &quot;exit&quot;, MyExit)
        do (go, &quot;script&quot;, params)
      &lt;/script&gt;
    &lt;/command&gt;[/code:hfzhk7pd]

MyExit is the name assigned to that &quot;up&quot; exit.
